title: [XLA:GPU] Replace block_id_to_tile_offsets_indexing with N-d tile_offsets_indexing map.
body:
[XLA:GPU] Replace block_id_to_tile_offsets_indexing with N-d tile_offsets_indexing map.

Currently we compute an indexing map from 1-d block_id to N-d tile offset for each TiledHloInstruction. We use that indexing map to deduplicate identical tiles. To get the map we compute delinearization of block_id in SymbolicTileAnalysis.

Composition and simplification of `block_id_to_tile_offsets_indexing` is actually very computationally intensive, because it the expression has a lot of mods and floordivs from delinearization. This is not necessary for out purposes.

After this change, `TiledHloComputation` will have N-d to M-d map from N-d tile indexing into M-d tile offsets of the instruction. This way expressions in the map 
are much smaller and easier to simplify (see changes in symbolic_tile_analysis_test).

This change has an additional benefit that we don't enforce 1-d launch grid at the early stage.

title: [TFLite] Use the same quantization info for broadcast_to input/output
body:
Broadcast_to has the operator property `restrict_same_input_output_scale=True`, however, this does not seem to be reflected by the mlir operator definitions in tfl_ops.td. This led to a case where the input quantization information differs to the output on creation of a quantized tflite flatbuffer file. This can cause type checking to fail at a later stage in mlir lowering (using tf-opt).

For example:
```
%3 = "tfl.broadcast_to"(%0, %2) : (tensor<!quant.uniform<i8<-127:127>:f32, 0.1:-128>>, tensor<3xi64>) -> tensor<1x1x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>
%6 = "tfl.scatter_nd"(%4, %3, %5) : (tensor<1x1x2xi32>, tensor<1x1x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>, tensor<3xi32>) -> tensor<1x224x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>
```
results in the following error:
```
error: 'tfl.scatter_nd' op quantization parameters violate the same scale constraint: !quant.uniform<i8<-127:127>:f32, 0.1:-128> vs. !quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>
```

forcing the input and output quantization information to match using the `SameOperandsAndResultsScale` attribute fixes this. The following will now be generated after model conversion instead:
```
%3 = "tfl.broadcast_to"(%0, %2) : (tensor<!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>, tensor<3xi64>) -> tensor<1x1x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>
%6 = "tfl.scatter_nd"(%4, %3, %5) : (tensor<1x1x2xi32>, tensor<1x1x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>, tensor<3xi32>) -> tensor<1x224x512x!quant.uniform<i8:f32, 0.1:-128>>
```
making later type checks happy.

title: Check if the Sharding custom-call instruction is the only one user of its operand.
body:
Check if the Sharding custom-call instruction is the only one user of its operand.

In `B = custom-call(A), custom_call_target="Sharding"`, we can set the sharding for `A` when all the three conditions are true.
1. Unspecified dims are empty. Otherwise, the sharding is open and can be further modified.
2. A has no sharding. We cannot overwrite the existing one.
3. A has only one user, which is B. Otherwise, the other users of A can also propagate shardings to A.

The first two conditions are checked before this cl. This cl add the third condition.
author: copybara-service[bot]

title: Update sharding propagation for dynamic slice and dynamic update slice.
body:
Update sharding propagation for dynamic slice and dynamic update slice.

For dynamice slice, there are two tensors involved, operand and result. The result is a "slice" of the operand. We propagate the sharding along non-slicing dimensions between these two tensors.

For dynmaic-update-slice, there are three tensors involved, operand_0, operand_1 (a.k.a. update), and result. Operand_0 and result has the full shape, while operand_1 is a slice of result.
* We directly propagate shardings between operand_0 and result, as if they are in an element-wise op.
* We propagate sharding along non-slicing dims between operand_1 and operand_0, between operand_1 and result.

title: [XLA:GPU] Add a data structure to efficiently deduplicate and store (Symbolic)TiledHloInstruction.
body:
[XLA:GPU] Add a data structure to efficiently deduplicate and store (Symbolic)TiledHloInstruction.

We use a combination of std::vector and absl::flat_hash_set to store and deduplicate tiled instruction. Basically the same logic is duplicated twice. Make it a template data structure is both `AnalyzeFusion` and `ComputeTiledHloInstructions`.

`symbolic_tile` now need to be set separately in `SymbolicTiledHloInstruction`, because computing the symbolic tile is an expensive operation and we would rather deduplicate the instruction first.
